AB  - Earlier this year, for the first time in Africa, an insurance policy that combines an Islamic-compliant financial instrument with innovative use of satellite imagery is compensating Muslim pastoralists for drought-induced losses suffered in Kenya's northeastern Wajir County, where livestock are valued at Ksh46 billion (US$550 million). Thirty women and 71 men in arid and semi-add Wajir are the first beneficiaries of livestock insurance that conforms to the Islamic concept of takaful, in which risks are shared among a group of participants. The pilot program is paying approximately Ksh500,000 (US$5,800) for losses suffered to herds of sheep, goats, cattle and camels during the long thy season that typically ends in March. The herds were insured last August by Takaful Insurance of Africa with an Index-Based Livestock Insurance product, branded as Index-Based Livestock Takaful. Takaful earns a management fee from participants who pay contributions to become members of a fund or risk pool.
