AB  - Livestock herders are often viewed as living a "backward" way of life, but a study carried out after Kenya's last devastating drought, in 2008-2009, finds that investments aimed at increasing the mobility of livestock herders could be the key to averting future food crises in arid lands. The report, "An Assessment of the Response to the 2008-2009 Drought in Kenya," suggests that herding makes better economic sense than crop agriculture in many of the arid and semi-arid lands that constitute 80% of the Horn of Africa. The best way to prevent famine in arid lands is to ensure herder access to critical dry-season grazing and watering areas. The best way to tap into the potential of the drylands is to invest in systems that support pastoral livelihoods, rather than ignoring them and hoping they go away, said International Livestock Research Institute ecologist Jan de Leeuw.
