AB  - Andhra Pradesh state was formed in 1956 under the re-organization of states act which was enacted to reconstitute the states on linguistic basis due to political and social compulsions. It was bifurcated into Andhra Pradesh (A P) and Telangana State (T S) in 2014 due to strong public demand and massive agitation involving various sections of the people from Telangana. Water resource of these states till recently was inter-dependant and inter-connected. After the bifurcation both the states are making rapid strides in utilizing the resource to full extent and enhance their GDP. The states are spending huge funds on social welfare to improve the living standards of people. Objective of the chapter is to evaluate the impact of water resources on socio-economic conditions, assess the return of investment on social sector and portray ground realities which could be a guide line for future spending as many states are allocating more and more funds for freebies and subsidies. The recently formed Andhra Pradesh state is spread over an area of 1.63 lakh sq.km and falls between north longitude 12° 37′ and 19° 09′ and east latitude 76° 45′ and 84° 47′. The state is divided into 13 districts and has 495.77 lakhs population with a decadal growth of 9.21% (Census 2011). The state is mainly drained by Godavari, Krishna, Pennar, Vamsadhara, Nagavalli, Gundlakamma rivers. A major part of the area is underlain by consolidated formations comprising gneissic rocks, Eastern Ghats and meta-sediments. The average annual rainfall ranges from 573 mm (Anantapuramu district) to 1165 mm (Srikakulam district) with an average of 950 mm. The agriculture and allied sectors support about 60% of the population. In general the net area irrigated constitutes about 45% of the net area sown. 60% of the irrigated area is covered by surface water and rest with groundwater. Long-term (1998-2017) water level trend indicates the falling trend of 0-5 m/yr in 60% of the area and rising trend of 0-3 m/yr in 40% of the area in the state. The falling trend of 1 to 2 m/yr was observed mostly in Kurnool, Kadapa, Anantapur, Chittoor districts which were many years ago declared as drought prone areas. The normal annual rainfall for entire state is 966 mm, during the last 8 years (2010-11 to 2018-19) rainfall was below normal in five years varying from -6 to -37 percentage deviation from normal, in 2018-19 rainfall was far below normal recoding -18% in SW monsoon and -58% in NE monsoon which exhibits the uncertainties in incidence of precipitation. Net area sown (including fish ponds) has decrease in the last five years from 40.26% of the total geographical area in 2013-14 to 37.11% in 2017-18. Similarly total cropped area has come down during said period by 4.19%. There was a significant fall in the average size of the landholding from 1.06 ha in 2010-11 to 0.94 ha 2015-16 and majority of farmers (89% of total number of holdings) operate ~<2 ha which constitute 58.34% of total land thus making the cultivation uneconomical. Andhra Pradesh is utilizing 308.703 TMC under existing projects creating an irrigation potential of 42.64 lakh ha up to March 2019 and 468.688 TMC is planned for utilization under ongoing projects for creating additional ayacut of 1.178 lakh ha and to stabilize 6.00 lakh ha. The state is an agrarian economy, has a low tax base and hence suffers from revenue instability. According to the advance estimates, the Gross State Domestic Product (GSDP) at constant (2011-12) prices for the year 2018-19 indicate a growth of 11.02% whereas growth rate of Gross State Value Added (GVSA) for agriculture was 10.78% and the per capita income (NSDP) at current prices in 2018-19 was 13.96%. The share of agriculture sector to the GSVA in 2018-19 was 33.64% at current prices (New Base 2011-12) and agriculture sector contribute 25 to 31% of GSDP. The State Govt. has initiated many measures to boost the agriculture sector and provide impetus to rural economy - some of them are-"YSR Rythu Bharosď scheme to farmer as well as tenant families, interest free loans to all the farmers who avail crop loans, crop insurance premium payment by the government, seeds were distributed with a subsidy value. In order to improve living standards of the people, the state is spending huge funds on social welfare under YSR Pensions, YSR Asara, Amma Vodi, Pedalandariki Illu, Madya Nishedam, Jalayagnam and Aarogyasri. Despite the financial adversities, the Government is going ahead with implementing social welfare schemes on saturation mode. Due to present political turmoil in the state on account of state capital and many other local issues including lockdown/slowdown due to CORONA virus the state is suffering from massive economic slowdown. Even though the state has potential natural resources and long coastline its financial position is in shambles with high public debt and continued political unrest. The newly carved out Telangana state from erstwhile Andhra Pradesh spreads over 1.12 lakh sq.km, falls between north latitude 15° 48' and 19° 54' and east longitude 77° 12'and 81° 50'. The state is divided into 31 districts out of 10 previous districts, and has the total population of 352 million (Census, 2011) with a decadal growth of 13.6%. The average annual rainfall is 905 mm, but it varies between 900 and 1500 mm in northern Telangana and 700 to 900 mm in southern Telangana. Among the 15 years (2004-'05 to 2018-'19) annual rainfall was less than normal in 9 years (mean was -19.4%), above normal in 6 years (mean was 16.5%) and on an average the mean deviation from normal rainfall for the past 15 years was -5.61% during this period. The state is drained by Godavari and Krishna rivers apart from many minor rivers and rivulets. The state has many major, medium irrigation projects (many are under development) which together have created an irrigation potential of 38.85 lakh ha (including area under stabilization). Majority of the state is occupied by consolidate rocks having limited groundwater potential. Uneven distribution of surface water sources especially in southern part and depleting groundwater levels significantly in northern part has took its toll on rural economy. The periodic monitoring records of both Central and State Govt. indicate that the decadal mean of May 2005-2016 shows a fall in water levels in 76% of the area and >2m decline was noticed in 31% of the area covering all the districts due to high dependence on groundwater (about 80% of irrigation requirement is met from groundwater). In order to reduce the declining water level trend and boost the minor irrigation the government has launched a gigantic programme for revival and restoration of surface water tanks under "Mission Kakatiya." Significant impact on the nearby aquifers was evident as compared to previous year, 0-4 m rise in water levels was observed in 30 % of wells and > 4 m rise was observed in 18 % of wells. Water resource is the controlling factor to propel the GSDP and socioeconomic condition of any agro-economy based state. About 55% of the state's population is dependent on farm activity for livelihood cultivating about 37.25% of total geographical area. The share of agriculture sector to the GSVA in 2016-17 was 15.3% at current prices. The average annual GSDP growth is 9.7% in the last five years and the per capita income was Rs. 2.05 lakhs in 2018-19. In order to further boost the GSDP and improve the living standards of people the government has taken up 32 major and 8 medium irrigation projects under "irrigation facilities to one crore acres" (4.05 million ha) of additional ayacut programme. Apart from focusing on development and management of water resource, the state has taken many welfare measures to enhance the average annual income of farmers and to improve the living standards of rural folk. These include input subsidies, investment support (Raythu Bandhu), social security (Raythu Bhima, Aasara Pensions Scheme), safe drinking water daily to each household (Mission Bhagiratha), round-the-clock power supply, quality health and education, decentralized administration, people participation in decision making process etc. Despite enormous efforts the expected improvements in living standards of rural people is not visible. Some of the important impediments could be climate vagaries, rise in capital as well as input expenditure, reduced operational land holding, lack of remunerative minimum support price (MSP) for agriculture products and diminishing rural employment opportunities. Many social welfare based freebies and subsidies offered to rural poor to improve their living standards has boomeranged, leading to acute scarcity of agriculture workforce. This chapter elaborates the present water resource potential of the two states, including agriculture productivity, socio-economic condition of farmers, impact of climate change on rural economy as well as side-effects of subsidies and social welfare schemes.
