AB  - Effective coastal management requires a fundamental understanding of the impacts of anthropogenic activities on sediment dynamics, yet it is challenging to isolate individual impacts in heavily altered regions. The Ayeyarwady Delta, Myanmar has been extensively deforested for agriculture but has few levees/polders. In this study, the relative resilience to subsidence was compared between a 45‐year‐old agricultural field and a nearby mangrove‐forest preserve. At both sites, water velocity and turbidity were measured in tidal channels, topography was mapped, and sediment cores were collected during 2018–2019. There was net sediment import at both sites due to sediment trapping by vegetation. Relative elevations were equivalent, suggesting that the field has aggraded at rates similar to the forest (0.7 cm/year). Unleveed fields may be less vulnerable to subsidence than leveed fields. However, uncertainties remain and the decision to replace mangroves with agricultural fields should weigh all the benefits provided by each environment.
